    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Maybe you can iterate over the map looking for the keys to remove and storing them in a separate collection. Then remove the collection of keys from the map. Modifying the map while iterating is usually frowned upon. This idea may be suspect if the map is very large. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 63531,
      "reputation" : 4067,
      "user_id" : 188014,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 89,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8d9bd7257394664df5ae7f17bb4c43e9?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "vickirk",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/188014/vickirk"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 2,
    "last_activity_date" : 1260490908,
    "creation_date" : 1260490908,
    "answer_id" : 1885047,
    "question_id" : 1884889,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>An alternative, more verbose way</p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;SomeObject&gt; toRemove = new ArrayList&lt;SomeObject&gt;();\nfor (SomeObject key: map.keySet()) {\n    if (something) {\n        toRemove.add(key);\n    }\n}\n\nfor (SomeObject key: toRemove) {\n    map.remove(key);\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
